         <p class="titulo_2_noticia_azul_oscuro">Presentaci&oacute;n Workshop SILE 2016 / presentation of ISEL Workshop 2016</p>
         <table style="width:100%" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="5">
         <tr>
         <td style="width:50%; vertical-align:top">
         <p>El Simposio Internacional sobre Literacidad en la Escuela (SILE) invita a presentar y discutir resultados de investigaci&oacute;n y sus implicancias pr&aacute;cticas, a nivel internacional, a quienes est&eacute;n interesados en el logro en lectura y escritura de estudiantes de educaci&oacute;n preescolar y educaci&oacute;n primaria.</p>
         <p>Para contribuir al pr&oacute;ximo Simposio SILE a realizarse en Francia en 2017, organizamos este evento cient&iacute;fico intermedio que se realizar&aacute; en Santiago de Chile en noviembre de 2016. Los investigadores (as) est&aacute;n invitados a presentar trabajos en dos &aacute;reas espec&iacute;ficas de SILE:</p>
         <ul>
         <li>Lectura y escritura en educaci&oacute;n primaria: aprendices y pr&aacute;cticas</li>
         <li> Alumnos con dificultad en el aprendizaje de la lectura y escritura, y aportes pr&aacute;cticos para ayudarlos a progresar</li>
         </ul>
         <p>En este Workshop de SILE 2016 queremos incluir por primera vez la visi&oacute;n latinoamericana acerca de estas &aacute;reas tem&aacute;ticas mediante la participaci&oacute;n de varios investigadores (as) de Am&eacute;rica latina.</p>
         <p> Los pa&iacute;ses latinoamericanos se caracterizan por su multiculturalidad y por sus grandes desigualdades sociales, lo que se traduce tambi&eacute;n en el aprendizaje de las competencias b&aacute;sicas de lectura y escritura, matem&aacute;tica y ciencias. Particularmente, en lectura y escritura encontramos que m&aacute;s de un tercio de los estudiantes de primeros a&ntilde;os de educaci&oacute;n b&aacute;sica presenta serios problemas en este &aacute;mbito. Estos son todav&iacute;a m&aacute;s agudos entre los estudiantes de ascendencia ind&iacute;gena, cuya primera lengua no es el espa&ntilde;ol y en escolares con alguna discapacidad o problema de aprendizaje.</p>
         <p>
           La investigaci&oacute;n en lectura y escritura es indispensable para aportar al conocimiento de c&oacute;mo aprenden los ni&ntilde;os en general y en particular, en sus contextos socioculturales. El intercambio entre investigadores de Latinom&eacute;rica, Am&eacute;rica del Norte y Europa en torno a esta problem&aacute;tica puede ser de gran utilidad para avanzar en pr&aacute;cticas m&aacute;s efectivas y pertinentes , as&iacute; como en la formaci&oacute;n inicial y continua de profesores y profesoras.</p>         
         </td>
         <td  style="width:50%; vertical-align:top">
         <p>
      The International Symposium for Educational Literacy (ISEL) invites to present and discuss the practical implications of research results on an international level to whom are interested in the reading and writing success of pre-school and primary students. </p>
         <p>In order to contribute to the next ISEL Symposium to be held in France on 2017, we organize this second intermediary scientific event to be held in Santiago de Chile next november 2016. Researchers are invited to focus on two specific ISEL areas:</p>
         <ul> 
          <li> Reading and writing in primary school: learners and practices</li>
           <li> Learning disabled students or with difficulties in reading-writing and the support practices to help them progress.</li></ul>  
         <p>In this 2016 edition of the ISEL workshop we are introducing for the first time the latinamerican view of this thematic areas through the participation of several latinamerican researchers. Latinamerican countries are characterized by their multiculturality and for having important social inequalities, which affects how children learn basic skills of literacy, numeracy and science.</p>
<p>
Particularly, in literacy, we found that more than a third of the students in their frist years of elementary education show important difficulties in reading and writing. These difficulties are even more severe in studients of indigenous background, whom their first language is not Spanish, and also in children with learning difficulties.</p>
<p>
Research in literacy is essential to contribute to the knowledge of how children learn in general and also in their particular sociocultural contexts. The exchange between reseachers of Latinamerica, North America and Europe around these issues could be useful to develop more effective literacy practices, and also support the initial and continous teacher training.</p></tr></table>
